<h1>Harmonic Minor</h1>
<p>
  The harmonic minor scale raises the seventh degree, creating a leading tone
  that pulls strongly to the tonic. In A harmonic minor the raised seventh is
  G#, which appears in the dominant chord <code>E7</code>.
</p>
<p>
  The <strong>ii°</strong> chord — <code>Bm7b5</code> (B half-diminished) —
  is the characteristic subdominant sonority in minor. Together with <code>E7</code>
  it forms the classic <strong>ii°–V7–i</strong> cadence: the minor-key
  equivalent of the ii–V–I found in major keys.
</p>
<p>
  The normaliser preserves the G# inside <code>E7</code> because the key is
  declared as <code>Am</code> and the raised seventh is expected in harmonic
  minor contexts.
</p>
